Mixing 16 and 32 Bit Code

    This is an example of how to call 16-bit functions and access 16-bit
    data from 32-bit code.  The example illustrates two different methods
    of achieving a 16 to 32 interface.  The first method uses function-
    declared entry points and is, in our opinion preferable to the somewhat
    cumbersome second method, which uses segment selectors.
	
    This example consists of the following files, in the
    EXAMPLES\MIX16W32 directory:

    PROT.C      32-bit code source.
    
    16BIT.ASM   Contains 16-bit data, and 16 bit-function to print 16-bit
                data.
                
    16BIT2.ASM  Contains a 16-bit function which calls interrupt 21/4C and
                exits.
                 
    MAKEFILE    Polymake-configured makefile for creating PROT1.EXE and
                PROT2.EXE using Watcom. 

    Note! No Microsoft buildable version of the MIX16W32 example is 
	    provided because Microsoft VC 4.x does not support mixed 16 and 32 
   	 bit code.

